title: For Sale/Trade:  Paratrooper M1 Carbine
postcontent: Vietnam era Plainfield M1 Carbine. Plainfield was not an "official" USGI rifle, however, they were built in the USA and sold to police, and overseas security forces. It was not un-common for these to be captured during the Vietnam conflict, and carried by our US soldiers. This one was captured and brought back by a Vietnam vet that carried it in it's original Para trooper configuration. This is a fairly rare Plainfield PM-30P Paratrooper. It is currently in a Korean era USGI stock, but it will come with it's original Para stock. You will get both stocks. It does not come with the canvas case shown in the picture. What you will receive is the Plainfield PM-30P M1 Carbine in the Korean era stock, the original Para stock, sling & oiler. The cool thing that many aren't aware of. The Plainfield M1 Carbines were built from blueprints from the USGI M1 Carbines, and parts are all milspec and interchangeable with USGI parts. This is being sold pending a deal I am working on another rifle. $800. Might consider trades.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M10A Remington, Martially marked WWI Trench Shotgun
postcontent: This is the real thing, not a replica somebody made from their grandad's goose-gun. The weapon was acquired by a friend's grandfather when he worked at a local post office and the postal service stopped keeping weapons in inventory. It is missing the wooden heat shield, sling-swivels, and bayonet adapter, just like nearly all of them are. All of the mounting points are in perfect condition. I can manufacture and install replica pieces for a price, if desired. The gun is fully functional, and has been perfectly maintained in a mechanical sense. The takedown mechanism works perfectly, and the barrel/receiver fit is tight and square. The bore is mirror-bright with no scratches or pitting. The muzzle is concentric, and cylinder-bore. The exterior is well worn with little remaining bluing/parkerizing (parkerizing on parts of the receiver indicates issue to the USMC), with the exception of the areas that were protected by the aforementioned missing accoutrements, which retain most of the original bluing. There is a serious blade-strike in the end of the magazine-tube, though it has no effect on the function or disassembly of the gun. It looks to me like defensive damage from warding of an edged weapon. I was told by the previous owner that his grandfather had used it occasionally as a grouse-gun, so the bulk of it's use was likely in military service. These guns were retained by the USMC until 1936. The barrel assembly and receiver assembly do not bear matching serial numbers, but both are in the correct range and configuration with correct markings for the emergency-purchased M10A's. The buttstock is a replacement, which is nearly uniform on these guns. As a combat vet, I consider weapons like this to be semi-sacred objects. I have no doubt that this weapon was used in combat, and likely saw some pretty ugly action given the nature of the exterior wear. I am not including any pictures given the extreme rarity of the item. I have some spare parts including a spare bolt and trigger/housing assembly I can include if you're interested. I will entertain serious offers only, and provide pictures on request to interested parties after a tentative offer is made. Most of the "blue books" don't even list this weapon, and those that do consider pricing to be speculative given the rarity of sale. I do not need to sell the gun, but feel it would be better-off in a more specific collection where it might be appreciated more. If I do not receive any attractive offers, I will likely donate the gun to a museum for public enjoyment. This is likely the only chance you'll ever have to own and original Remington M10A "trench" gun. Any sale or inspection will be conducted in person at a licensed dealer's premises in the Madison, WI area. I store my collectible/high-value items in a secure off-site premises, so some planning will be required.

CZ SP-01 Phantom 9mm

The CZ 75 SP-01 was the first full size handgun (4.61” barrel) from CZ to featuring improved manufacturing technology and ergonomics of the world famous and NATO-approved CZ 75. It features a 1913 accessory rail, rubber grips, and CZ’s corrosion resistant black polycoat finish. The SP-01 pistol is based on the CZ 75 (SA/DA) platform. The SP-01 utilizes an extended beavertail to protect shooter’s strong hand and to offer a deeper and more secure grip. The grip geometry has checkering in key areas on the front and back straps, and redistribution of mass provided by the accessory rail noticeably decreases the perceived recoil, and allows for more rapid target acquisition and transition. title: For Sale:  Jennings 9mm 9+1
postcontent:
Here is a nice handgun for the right price!

Jennings / Bryco Arms which is not full of "slop" thus this piece has not been fired very much at all.

The barrel is stationary while relying on the blowback system to actuate slide upon firing, ejection of spent casing, and feeding of charged round.  

Here is how one can make the gun jam:  never clean or lubricate it; use cheap / dirty ammunition; or limp wrist the weapon on recoil.

The visible "cartridge in chamber" is a great feature.  to prevent slide bite - use common sense....use you thumb to hold down your other thumb, thus keeping the "web" of your hand away from slide in motion.

I have no reservations at all relying on this gun.  I do my part well, the machinery performs well.
